sec.p:
Controller 1 and 2 select their own control signal u1∗\begin{document}$u_{1}^{*}$\end{document} or u2∗\begin{document}$u_{2}^{*}$\end{document}, which considers their respective costs. We can define individual cost functions J1 and J2 as:
(2)
J1=12∑k=0N−1(xkTQ1xk+u1,kTR11u1,k)+12xNTQ1,NxN \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{1}=\frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\left(x_{k}^{T} Q_{1} x_{k}+u_{1, k}^{T} R_{11} u_{1, k}\right)+\frac{1}{2} x_{N}^{T} Q_{1, N} x_{N} \tag{2} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(3)
J2=12∑k=0N−1(xkTQ2xk+u2,kTR22u2,k)+12xNTQ2,NxN \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{2}=\frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\left(x_{k}^{T} Q_{2} x_{k}+u_{2, k}^{T} R_{22} u_{2, k}\right)+\frac{1}{2} x_{N}^{T} Q_{2, N} x_{N} \tag{3} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
Here J1 is the individual cost for controller 1 (e.g., self) and J2 is the individual cost for controller 2 (e.g., partner). N is the final step, which represents the end of a trial. The term Q penalizes deviations of the center cursor relative to each target.

Depending on the experimental condition, we modelled i) a task-relevant target using a higher value of Q, and ii) a task-irrelevant target using a lower value of Q. The term R penalizes the control signal (u), which would relate to an energetic cost. Further, we define a joint cost function as:
(4)
J1α1=J1+α1J2 \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}=J_{1}+\alpha_{1} J_{2} \tag{4} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(5)
J2α2=J2+α2J1, \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{2}^{\alpha_{2}}=J_{2}+\alpha_{2} J_{1}, \tag{5} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
where αi ∈ [0, 1] determines the degree to which controller i considers their partner’s cost function.

The optimal control signal for controller 1 (u1,k∗)\begin{document}$\left(u_{1, k}^{*}\right)$\end{document} and controller 2 (u1,k∗)\begin{document}$\left(u_{1, k}^{*}\right)$\end{document} is determined by the time-varying feedback gains F1 and F2 that minimize the joint cost function J1α1\begin{document}$J_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}$\end{document} and J2α2\begin{document}$J_{2}^{\alpha_{2}}$\end{document} respectively:
(6)
u1,k∗=−F1,kx^1,k \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} u_{1, k}^{*}=-F_{1, k} \hat{x}_{1, k} \tag{6} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(7)
u2,k∗=−F2,kx^2,k \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} u_{2, k}^{*}=-F_{2, k} \hat{x}_{2, k} \tag{7} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
Here, x^i,k\begin{document}$\hat{x}_{i, k}$\end{document} for i = {1, 2} is controller i’s posterior estimate of the state (see Methods). The feedback gains F1 and F2 constitute a Nash equilibrium solution to the linear quadratic game defined by eqs. 1-5. Throughout, the feedback gains determine hand movement and visuomotor feedback responses. The Nash equilibrium solution F1 that minimizes J1α1\begin{document}$J_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}$\end{document} can utilize knowledge of the partner’s control policy F2 through the coupled algebraic Riccati equations (see Supplementary C).

Each hand in the linear-quadratic game was modelled as a point mass. Throughout, the subscript i refers to each controller, where i = {1, 2}. We describe the model with controller 1 as the self and controller 2 as the partner. The continuous-time dynamics of the point mass representing the hand of controller 1 were as follows:
(8)
mp¨1=−bp˙1+f1 \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} m \ddot{p}_{1}=-b \dot{p}_{1}+f_{1} \tag{8} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(9)
τf˙1=u1−f1 \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \tau \dot{f}_{1}=u_{1}-f_{1} \tag{9} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
where m1 is the mass of the hand, p1 is the two-dimensional position vector of the point mass, b is the viscous constant, f1 is the two-dimensional controlled forces, and u1 is the two-dimensional control signal for controller 1. m was set to 1.5 kg, b was set to 0.1 N · s · m−1 and the time constant of the linear filter (τ) was set to 20 ms. These parameters were identical for controller 1 and controller 2. The parameters were selected so that the model visuomotor feedback response magnitudes closely matched the measured visuomotor feedback response magnitudes.

Controllers 1 and 2 each move their hand and interact to move the center cursor (cc). The dynamics of the center cursor are:
(10)
p˙cc=p˙1+p˙22. \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \dot{p}_{c c}=\frac{\dot{p}_{1}+\dot{p}_{2}}{2} . \tag{10} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
The state vector x is
(11)
x=[p1,p1˙,f1,p2,p2˙,f2,pcc,ptarget]T \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} x=\left[p_{1}, \dot{p_{1}}, f_{1}, p_{2}, \dot{p_{2}}, f_{2}, p_{c c}, p_{\text {target }}\right]^{T} \tag{11} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
where each element in the vector contains an x and y dimension. T is the transpose operator. The system dynamics were transformed into a system of first order differential equations and discretized. The linear-quadratic state space model is
(12)
xk+1=Axk+B1u1,k+B2u2,k. \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} x_{k+1}=A x_{k}+B_{1} u_{1, k}+B_{2} u_{2, k} . \tag{12} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
Here xk is the state vector at time k and A is the dynamics matrix. Bi maps the control vector ui,k of player i to muscle force fi,k at time k. A, B1, and B2 are fully defined in Supplementary C.

Like previous work, we used a linear Kalman filter to model participants sensory estimates of the state variables. The posterior state estimate x^1,k\begin{document}$\hat{x}_{1, k}$\end{document} of controller 1 is obtained using an online filter of the form:
(15)
x^1,k=x¯1,k+K1,k(y1,k−H1x¯1,k) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \hat{x}_{1, k}=\bar{x}_{1, k}+K_{1, k}\left(y_{1, k}-H_{1} \bar{x}_{1, k}\right) \tag{15} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(16)
x¯1,k=Ax^1,k−1+B1u1,k+B2u2,k. \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \bar{x}_{1, k}=A \hat{x}_{1, k-1}+B_{1} u_{1, k}+B_{2} u_{2, k} . \tag{16} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
Here x¯1,k\begin{document}$\bar{x}_{1, k}$\end{document} is the prior prediction of the state. That is, we assume the sensorimotor system obtains a prior prediction of the states using an accurate internal model of the state dynamics, which includes a prediction of the partner’s motor command. The prior prediction uses the previous posterior estimate (x^1,k−1)\begin{document}$\left(\hat{x}_{1, k-1}\right)$\end{document}, the efference copy (u1), and the prediction of the partner’s motor command (u2).

The goal of each controller i is to move the state of the system from an initial state x0 to a target state xtarget at the final time step N by each minimizing a quadratic cost functional Ji:
(17)
J1=12∑k=0N−1(xkTQ1xk+u1,kTR11u1,k)+12xNTQ1,NxN \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{1}=\frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\left(x_{k}^{T} Q_{1} x_{k}+u_{1, k}^{T} R_{11} u_{1, k}\right)+\frac{1}{2} x_{N}^{T} Q_{1, N} x_{N} \tag{17} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(18)
J2=12∑k=0N−1(xkTQ2xk+u2,kTR22u2,k)+12xNTQ2,NxN. \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{2}=\frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\left(x_{k}^{T} Q_{2} x_{k}+u_{2, k}^{T} R_{22} u_{2, k}\right)+\frac{1}{2} x_{N}^{T} Q_{2, N} x_{N} . \tag{18} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
Here J1 is the individual cost for controller 1 (e.g. self) and J2 is the individual cost for controller 2 (e.g. partner). The quadratic costs penalize deviations from the target state at the final step (Qi,N) and controller i’s control signals (Rii). We then define the joint cost functions as
(19)
J1α1=J1+α1J2 \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}=J_{1}+\alpha_{1} J_{2} \tag{19} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(20)
J2α2=J2+α2J1, \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{2}^{\alpha_{2}}=J_{2}+\alpha_{2} J_{1}, \tag{20} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
where αi ∈ [0, 1] determines the degree to which controller i considers their partner’s costs.

The optimal control signal for controllers 1 and 2 is defined as
(21)
u1,k∗=−F1,kx^1,k \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} u_{1, k}^{*}=-F_{1, k} \hat{x}_{1, k} \tag{21} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(22)
u2,k∗=−F2,kx^2,k, \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} u_{2, k}^{*}=-F_{2, k} \hat{x}_{2, k}, \tag{22} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
where x^i,k\begin{document}$\hat{x}_{i, k}$\end{document} is the posterior estimate and Fi,k is the time-varying feedback gain for controller i. The feedback gains Fi,k, also known as the control policy, are the Nash equilibrium solution to the linear quadratic game described by Eq. 11 and Eqs. 16-19.75 See Supplementary C for details.

Controller 1 and 2 select their own control signal u1∗\begin{document}$u_{1}^{*}$\end{document} or u2∗\begin{document}$u_{2}^{*}$\end{document}, which considers their respective costs. We can define an individual cost function J1 and J2 as:
(2)
J1=12∑k=0N−1(xk⊤Q1,kxk+u1,k⊤R11u1,k)+12xN⊤Q1,NxN \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{1}=\frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\left(x_{k}^{\top} Q_{1, k} x_{k}+u_{1, k}^{\top} R_{11} u_{1, k}\right)+\frac{1}{2} x_{N}^{\top} Q_{1, N} x_{N} \tag{2} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(3)
J2=12∑k=0N−1(xk⊤Q2,kxk+u2,k⊤R22u2,k)+12xN⊤Q2,NxN. \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{2}=\frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\left(x_{k}^{\top} Q_{2, k} x_{k}+u_{2, k}^{\top} R_{22} u_{2, k}\right)+\frac{1}{2} x_{N}^{\top} Q_{2, N} x_{N} . \tag{3} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
Here J1 is the individual cost for controller 1 (e.g., self) and J2 is the individual cost for controller 2 (e.g., partner). N is the final step, which represents the end of a trial. The term Q penalizes deviations of the center cursor relative to each target. We modelled i) a task-relevant target using a higher value of Q, and ii) a task-irrelevant target using a lower value of Q. The term Rii penalizes controller i’s control signals, which can be thought of as an energetic cost. See further below and Table 1 for the fully defined matrices Q and R. We define a joint cost function as:

(4)

J1α1=J1+α1J2
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}=J_{1}+\alpha_{1} J_{2} \tag{4} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}




(5)

J2α2=J2+α2J1,
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{2}^{\alpha_{2}}=J_{2}+\alpha_{2} J_{1}, \tag{5} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}



where αi ∈ [0, 1] determines the degree to which controller i considers their partner’s cost function. Specifically, the term αi was applied to both the partner’s state cost and energetic cost:

(6)

Q1,kα1=max(Q1,k,α1Q2,k)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} Q_{1, k}^{\alpha_{1}}=\max \left(Q_{1, k}, \alpha_{1} Q_{2, k}\right) \tag{6} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}




(7)

Q2,kα2=max(Q2,k,α2Q1,k)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} Q_{2, k}^{\alpha_{2}}=\max \left(Q_{2, k}, \alpha_{2} Q_{1, k}\right) \tag{7} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}




(8)

R12=α1R11
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} R_{12}=\alpha_{1} R_{11} \tag{8} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}




(9)

R21=α2R22.
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle R_{21}=\alpha_{2} R_{22} .$$\end{document}



Q1α1\begin{document}$Q_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}$\end{document} reflects how much controller 1 considers controller 2’s state cost (i.e., controller 1’s partner stabilizing the center cursor in the partner target). Q2α2\begin{document}$Q_{2}^{\alpha_{2}}$\end{document} reflects how much controller 2 considers controller 1’s state cost (i.e., controller 2’s partner stabilizing the center cursor in the partner target). Specifically, we reasoned that each controller would only consider their partner’s state cost if their partner’s state cost was higher (i.e. higher value of an element in Q) . We implemented this logic with the max function in Eqs. 6-7. That is, for controller 1, if the self target was relevant then Q1,kα1=Q1,k\begin{document}$Q_{1, k}^{\alpha_{1}}=Q_{1, k}$\end{document} and if the self target was irrelevant and partner target was relevant then Q1,kα1=αQ2,k\begin{document}$Q_{1, k}^{\alpha_{1}}=\alpha Q_{2, k}$\end{document}. Additionally, R12 reflects how much controller 1 considers controller 2’s energetic cost of movement by multiplying alpha by its own energetic cost. Likewise, R21 reflects how much controller 2 considers controller 1’s energetic cost of movement. We can rewrite the joint cost functions in Eqs. 4-5 in the quadratic form as:

(10)

J1α1=12∑k=0N−1(xk⊤Q1,kα1xk+u1,k⊤R11u1,k+u2,k⊤R12u2,k)+12xN⊤Q1,Nα1xN
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}=\frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\left(x_{k}^{\top} Q_{1, k}^{\alpha_{1}} x_{k}+u_{1, k}^{\top} R_{11} u_{1, k}+u_{2, k}^{\top} R_{12} u_{2, k}\right)+\frac{1}{2} x_{N}^{\top} Q_{1, N}^{\alpha_{1}} x_{N} \tag{10} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}




(11)

J2α2=12∑k=0N−1(xk⊤Q2,kα2xk+u2,k⊤R22u2,k+u1,k⊤R21u1,k)+12xN⊤Q2,Nα2xN.
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} J_{2}^{\alpha_{2}}=\frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\left(x_{k}^{\top} Q_{2, k}^{\alpha_{2}} x_{k}+u_{2, k}^{\top} R_{22} u_{2, k}+u_{1, k}^{\top} R_{21} u_{1, k}\right)+\frac{1}{2} x_{N}^{\top} Q_{2, N}^{\alpha_{2}} x_{N} . \tag{11} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

x0 reflects the initial state at the start of each simulation, matching the experimental design.
Writing out xQix from the cost function Ji gives the state cost:
StateCost1=wv∗(v1,x2+v1,y2)+wf∗(f1,x2+f1,y2)+wy∗(p1,y−p2,y)2+w1,ccx∗(pcc,x−pct,x)2+wccy∗(pcc,y−pct,y)2StateCost2=wv∗(v2,x2+v2,y2)+wf∗(f2,x2+f2,y2)+wy∗(p1,y−p2,y)2+w2,ccx∗(pcc,x−pct,x)2+wccy∗(pcc,y−pct,y)2 \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} \text { StateCost }_{1}= & w_{v} *\left(v_{1, x}^{2}+v_{1, y}^{2}\right)+w_{f} *\left(f_{1, x}^{2}+f_{1, y}^{2}\right) \\ & +w_{y} *\left(p_{1, y}-p_{2, y}\right)^{2}+w_{1, c c_{x}} *\left(p_{c c, x}-p_{c t, x}\right)^{2}+w_{c c_{y}} *\left(p_{c c, y}-p_{c t, y}\right)^{2} \\ \text { StateCost }_{2}= & w_{v} *\left(v_{2, x}^{2}+v_{2, y}^{2}\right)+w_{f} *\left(f_{2, x}^{2}+f_{2, y}^{2}\right) \\ & +w_{y} *\left(p_{1, y}-p_{2, y}\right)^{2}+w_{2, c c_{x}} *\left(p_{c c, x}-p_{c t, x}\right)^{2}+w_{c c_{y}} *\left(p_{c c, y}-p_{c t, y}\right)^{2}\end{aligned}$$\end{document}
The control costs for controller 1 and controller 2 are:
R11=[r00r]R22=[r00r] \begin{document}$$\displaystyle R_{11}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}r & 0 \\ 0 & r\end{array}\right] \quad R_{22}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}r & 0 \\ 0 & r\end{array}\right]$$\end{document}
Note that all the parameter weightings for the state and control costs are held constant across all experimental conditions except for w1,ccx\begin{document}$w_{1, c c_{x}}$\end{document} and w2,ccx\begin{document}$w_{2, c c_{x}}$\end{document} which reflected the width of the target. For values of all parameters, see Table 1.

The optimal control signal for controller 1 ((u1,k∗)\begin{document}$\left(u_{1, k}^{*}\right)$\end{document}) and controller 2 ((u1,k∗)\begin{document}$\left(u_{1, k}^{*}\right)$\end{document}) is determined by the time-varying feedback gains F1 and F2 that minimize the joint cost function J1α1\begin{document}$J_{1}^{\alpha_{1}}$\end{document} and J2α2\begin{document}$J_{2}^{\alpha_{2}}$\end{document} respectively:

(12)

u1,k∗=−F1,kx^1,k
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} u_{1, k}^{*}=-F_{1, k} \hat{x}_{1, k} \tag{12} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}




(13)

u2,k∗=−F2,kx^2,k
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} u_{2, k}^{*}=-F_{2, k} \hat{x}_{2, k} \tag{13} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}



Here, x^i,k\begin{document}$\hat{x}_{i, k}$\end{document} for i = {1, 2} is controller i’s posterior estimate of the state (see Methods in the main manuscript). The feedback gains F1 and F2 constitute a Nash equilibrium solution to the linear quadratic game defined above (from Basar and Olsder Chapter 6, Corollary 6.11):

(14)

F1,k=(R11+B1⊤P1,kB1)−1(B1⊤P1,kA−B1⊤P1,kB2F2,k)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} F_{1, k}=\left(R_{11}+B_{1}^{\top} P_{1, k} B_{1}\right)^{-1}\left(B_{1}^{\top} P_{1, k} A-B_{1}^{\top} P_{1, k} B_{2} F_{2, k}\right) \tag{14} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}




(15)

F2,k=(R22+B2⊤P2,kB2)−1(B2⊤P2,kA−B2⊤P2,kB1F1,k).
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} F_{2, k}=\left(R_{22}+B_{2}^{\top} P_{2, k} B_{2}\right)^{-1}\left(B_{2}^{\top} P_{2, k} A-B_{2}^{\top} P_{2, k} B_{1} F_{1, k}\right) . \tag{15} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}



Importantly, note that the solution F1,k contains the term B1⊤P1,kB2F2,k\begin{document}$B_{1}^{\top} P_{1, k} B_{2} F_{2, k}$\end{document}
,kB2F2,k demonstrating knowledge of the partner’s feedback gains F2,k. In our modeling framework, this knowledge of the partner’s control policy reflects a partner representation.

Here, Pi,k is the solution to the set of coupled Riccati equations derived via dynamic programming for a linear quadratic game.
(16)
P1,k=Sk⊤P1,k+1Sk+F1,k⊤R11F1,k+F2,k⊤R12F2,k+Q1,kα \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} P_{1, k}=S_{k}^{\top} P_{1, k+1} S_{k}+F_{1, k}^{\top} R_{11} F_{1, k}+F_{2, k}^{\top} R_{12} F_{2, k}+Q_{1, k}^{\alpha} \tag{16} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(17)
P2,k=Sk⊤P2,k+1Sk+F2,k⊤R22F2,k+F1,k⊤R21F1,k+Q2,kα \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} P_{2, k}=S_{k}^{\top} P_{2, k+1} S_{k}+F_{2, k}^{\top} R_{22} F_{2, k}+F_{1, k}^{\top} R_{21} F_{1, k}+Q_{2, k}^{\alpha} \tag{17} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
where Sk = A − B1F1,k − B2F2,k

Each controller receives delayed sensory feedback of its own hand position, velocity, and force, as well as the partner’s hand position and velocity. Further, each controller receives delayed sensory feedback of the center cursor position and target position. To incorporate sensory delays, we augmented the state vector with previous states.2,3
(18)
xkaug=[xk,xk−1,…,xk−nδv]⊤ \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} x_{k}^{a u g}=\left[x_{k}, x_{k-1}, \ldots, x_{k-n_{\delta v}}\right]^{\top} \tag{18} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
Here δv = 110 ms to reflect the transmission delay associated with vision and aligned the model and experimental visuomotor response onset times. This value was converted into time steps in our program (nδv = 11). To accommodate the augmented state vector, we also augmented A, Bi, and Qi:
Aaug=[A0nx×nxdInxd0nxd×nx]Baug=[B0nxd×nu]Qaug=[Q0nx×nxd0nxd×nx0nxd×nxd] \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{array}{r}A^{a u g}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}A & 0_{n_{x} \times n_{x d}} \\ I_{n_{x d}} & 0_{n_{x d} \times n_{x}}\end{array}\right] \\ B^{a u g}=\left[\begin{array}{c}B \\ 0_{n_{x d} \times n_{u}}\end{array}\right] \\ Q^{a u g}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}Q & 0_{n_{x} \times n_{x d}} \\ 0_{n_{x d} \times n_{x}} & 0_{n_{x d} \times n_{x d}}\end{array}\right]\end{array}$$\end{document}
Here nx is the total number of states (16), nu is the number of control states (2), and nxd is the total number of time delayed states (nx · nδv = 176). Ip is the square identity matrix with nxd rows and nxd columns. 0 is a matrix with all zeros of the specified dimensions. Baug is designed so the controllers only act on the current (non-delayed) state. Qaug is designed so the controllers only incur a cost on the current (non-delayed) state.

Ciaug\begin{document}$C_{i}^{a u g}$\end{document} is an observation matrix designed to selectively observe some of the delayed states. First we define C1 and C2:
Here controller i observes all states except their partner’s force production in both the x and y dimension. We augment both observation matrices to only observe the delayed state.
Ciaug=[014×pCi] \begin{document}$$\displaystyle C_{i}^{a u g}=\left[\begin{array}{ll}0_{14 \times p} & C_{i}\end{array}\right]$$\end{document}
To minimize extra notation, we drop the aug superscript moving forward. Like previous work, we used a linear Kalman filter to model participants sensory estimates of the state variables.4 The posterior state estimate x^1,k\begin{document}$\hat{x}_{1, k}$\end{document} of controller 1 is obtained using an online filter of the form:
(22)
x^1,k=x¯1,k+K1,k(y1,k−H1x¯1,k) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \hat{x}_{1, k}=\bar{x}_{1, k}+K_{1, k}\left(y_{1, k}-H_{1} \bar{x}_{1, k}\right) \tag{22} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(23)
x¯1,k=Ax^1,k−1+B1u1,k+B2u2,k+ω¯1,k. \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \bar{x}_{1, k}=A \hat{x}_{1, k-1}+B_{1} u_{1, k}+B_{2} u_{2, k}+\bar{\omega}_{1, k} .$$\end{document}
Here x¯1,k\begin{document}$\bar{x}_{1, k}$\end{document} is the prior prediction of the state corrupted by Gaussian noise ω¯1,k\begin{document}$\bar{\omega}_{1, k}$\end{document} with zero mean and standard deviation of 1e-5. We assume the sensorimotor system obtains a noisy prior prediction of the states using an internal model of the state dynamics, which includes a prediction of the partner’s motor command. The prior prediction uses the previous posterior estimate ((x^1,k−1)\begin{document}$\left(\hat{x}_{1, k-1}\right)$\end{document}), the efference copy (u1), and the prediction of the partner’s motor command (u2).

The prior prediction of the state is updated using sensory measurements to obtain the posterior estimate x^1\begin{document}$\hat{x}_{1}$\end{document} (Eq. 22). The sequence of Kalman gains K1 and K2 were updated recursively according to the classic algorithm:
(24)
Pi,k+1prior=AdPi,kpostAd⊤+Vi,k \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} P_{i, k+1}^{\text {prior }}=A_{d} P_{i, k}^{\text {post }} A_{d}^{\top}+V_{i, k} \tag{24} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(25)
Si,k+1=CiPi,k+1priorCi⊤+Wk+1 \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} S_{i, k+1}=C_{i} P_{i, k+1}^{\text {prior }} C_{i}^{\top}+W_{k+1} \tag{25} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(26)
Ki,k+1=Pi,k+1priorCi⊤Si,k+1−1 \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} K_{i, k+1}=P_{i, k+1}^{\text {prior }} C_{i}^{\top} S_{i, k+1}^{-1} \tag{26} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
(27)
